  "why": "The paper provides substantive diagnostic insight into discovered failures by characterizing their properties and showing how failures correlate with input perturbations and layer-output statistics (density, correlation, shape). For example, the authors analyze adversarial and adversarial-perturbed inputs to show that some prior coverage metrics (NBC/SNAC/DSC) respond to input dissimilarity rather than true fault-revealing capability, and they demonstrate that stylizing/blurring mutations expose the models' texture-bias. These analyses link observed failures to specific observable behaviors (sensitivity to dissimilarity/adversarial perturbations, texture reliance) and to model-internal distributional signals (covariance/density changes). However, the paper does not perform deeper root-cause tracing such as linking failures to corrupted or biased training labels or to overfitting across datasets, nor does it systematically trace individual failure instances back to concrete training-data issues or propose targeted remediation based on such root-cause attribution. Therefore the paper offers partial (characterization and correlation) diagnostic understanding but stops short of a full causal root-cause analysis required for a High rating.",
